<h2>Storm Gloria causes major flooding in Spain</h2>
<br><br>
The storm Gloria was a severe event that took place between 18 and 23
January 2020 across parts of Spain and France. Winds up to 140 km/h
(87 mph), violent waves, and heavy snow left a trail of destruction
across Spain. Storm surge also swept 3 km (1.8 miles) inland in
Tarragona province, affecting rice paddies and the ecosystem.
<br><br>
Major flooding event was caused by both major storm surge (from severe
winds) and excessive rainfall amount. Some areas received more than
300 mm of rain within a time period of 48-hours. A huge amount of
snow has accumulated across the eastern Pyrenees, as strong and
persisting orographic snowfall was occurring. The highest mountains
received more than 150 cm of snow, significantly enhancing avalanche
danger.
<br><br>
The storm affected wide areas of Spain, in particular along the
southern and eastern coasts, bringing strong winds, high waves, storm
surge and torrential rain. AEMET reported wind gusts of 115 km/h in
Oliva, Valencia, on 20 January and 106 km/h in Barcelona the next
day. Huge waves, reportedly up to 14.8 metres, smashed into coastal
areas of Valencia, Catalonia and the Balearic Islands. Several areas
recorded more than 180 mm of rainfall in 24 hours during the storm,
including Barx in Valencia Province (190.4 mm on 20 January), Horta de
Sant Joan in Tarragona Province (227.4 mm on 21 January), Sant Hilari
in Girona (183.2 mm on 22 January) and Coín in Málaga (183.0 mm on
23 January). Severe flooding was reported in areas around Girona after
the Ter river broke its banks on 23 January. The overflowing
Guadalhorce and Campanillas rivers caused flash flooding and damage in
the province of M&#225;laga on 24 January. The Guadalhorce river
reached 4.70 metres on 25 January, with floods leaving residents
trapped in their homes in C&#225;rtama.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2020/Analyse_2020011900.png"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2020/Analyse_2020011900.png" width="400px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1: Synoptic situation at 19 January 2020 00 UTC, KNMI.</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
In the analyses (Figure 1) one can see the strong low pressure area
over the SE-parts of Spain. Even in the upper air regions the low was
well developed. The cold upper air led to unstable conditions. Extreme
wind- and flooding conditions could develop due to a very strong
gradient and the interaction with the topography.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/jan2020/Eumetsat-storm-spain-january-19-2020.jpg" target="_blank"><img alt="" src="../images/jan2020/Eumetsat-storm-spain-january-19-2020.jpg" width="400px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 2: Satellite image at 19 January 2020 12 UTC, Eumetsat.</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
<strong>Record breaking significant wave height</strong>
<br><br>
Storm Gloria had broken several significant wave height records
according to the network of deep-sea buoys. The historical maximum or
highest data measured in the western Mediterranean has been claimed by
an ocean buoy near Valencia. Gloria produced a record-breaking
significant wave height of 8.44 meters (27.69 feet) off the port city
of Valencia, breaking the previous significant wave height record in
the Mediterranean Sea of 8.15 m (26.73 feet), set in Mahon, Menorca in
2003.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for January 2020</h2>
<br><br>
After a relatively winter-poor December, also January was far from
wintery conditions across most parts of Europe with monthly mean air
temperatures much above or even exceptionally above the long-term mean
(Figure 10). Average temperatures were especially high over large
parts of northeastern Europe (Scandinavia, Western Russia and the
Baltic countries) reaching values greater than 6&deg;C above the
1981-2010 January average. In this region, mean minimum temperatures
(Figure 3) were around +8&deg;C above normal and the coldest nights
(Figures 4) were even more than 10&deg;C too warm. As a consequence,
the number of frost days (FD) was much lower. Over the Baltic
countries and southern Sweden there were up to 20 frost days less than
normal (Figure 5). An interesting patch of normal to below-normal
temperatures is visible over southern and southeastern Europe
(Hungary, east Croatia and northern Serbia), where there were a number
of cold air intrusions from the north and northeast. Here more frost
days than normal were recorded (around four).
